olonial Theory, India and \"The Mystic East\" | publisher =Taylor & Francis e-Library}}\n*{{citation |last =Schubring|first=Walther|title=The Doctrine of the Jainas: Described After the Old Sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sYXKD2IAu00C|year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0933-8}}\n* {{Citation | last =Daniel | first =P.S. | year =2000 | title =Hindu Response to Religious Pluralism | publisher =Kant Publications | isbn =978-8186218105 | url =http://www.easternbookcorporation.com/moreinfo.php?txt_searchstring=3165}}\n*{{citation |last =Jaini|first=Padmanabh S.|title=Collected Papers on Jaina Studies|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HPggiM7y1aYC|year=2000a|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1691-6|chapter=Jaina Purana: A counter Puranic Tradition}}\n*{{citation |last =Jaini|first=Padmanabh S.|title=Collected Papers on Jaina Studies|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HPggiM7y1aYC|year=2000b|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1691-6|chapter=Jina Rsabha as an Avatara of Visnu}}\n*{{citation |last =Glasenapp|first=Helmuth von|title=Jainism: An Indian Religion of Salvation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WzEzXDk0v6sC|year=1999|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1376-2}}\n*{{citation |last =Feynes|first=R.C.C|title=The Lives of the Jain Elders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=quNpKVqABGMC&pg=PR24|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-283227-6}}\n*{{citation |last =Jaini|first=Padmanabh S.|title=The Jaina Path of Purification|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wE6v6ahxHi8C|year=1998|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1578-0}}\n* {{citation |editor=[[John E. Cort]] |title=Open Boundaries: Jain Communities and Cultures in Indian History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoHfm7BgqTgC |publisher=[[SUNY Press]] |date=1998 |isbn=978-0-7914-3785-8 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Babb|first=Lawrence A.|title=Absent Lord: Ascetics and Kings in a Jain Ritual Culture|url=https://archive.org/details/absentlordasceti0000babb|url-access=registration|year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91708-8}}\n* {{Citation | last =Rambachan | first =Anatanand | year =1994 | title =The Limits of Scripture: Vivekananda's Reinterpretation of the Vedas | publisher =University of Hawaii Press}}\n*Nalini Balbir {{citation |last=Sharma|first=Arvind|title=Religion and Women|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SPmlL55RNAQC&pg=PA121|year=1994|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-1690-7|page=121}}\n* {{citation |last=Dundas |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Dundas |title=The Jains |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X8iAAgAAQBAJ |edition=Second |date=2002 |orig-year=1992 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-0-415-26605-5 }}\n*{{citation |last =Ramanujan|first=A.K. |editor=Paula Richman|title=Many R\u0101m\u0101ya\u1e47as: The Diversity of a Narrative Tradition in South Asia|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XkifYfljHP4C|year=1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-07589-4|chapter=Three Hundred Ramayanas: Five Examples and Three Thoughts on Translation}}\n* {{Citation | last =Zimmer | first =Heinrich | year =1989 | title =Philosophies of India | publisher =Princeton University Press}}\n* {{Citation | last =Embree | first =Ainslie T. | authorlink = Ainslie Embree | year =1988 | title =Sources of Indian Tradition. Second Edition. volume One. From the beginning to 1800 | publisher =Columbia University Press}}\n*{{citation\n|last1=Zimmer|first1=Heinrich|title=Philosophies Of India\n|year=1953|editor=Joseph Campbell|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul Ltd\n|location=London, E.C. 4\n|url=https://archive.org/details/Philosophy.of.India.by.Heinrich.Zimmer\n|isbn=978-8120807396|authorlink=Heinrich Zimmer}}\n*{{citation |title=Risabha Deva - The Founder of Jainism|first=Champat Rai|last=Jain|publisher=The Indian Press Limited|location=[[Allahabad]]|date=1929|url=https://archive.org/details/RisabhaDeva-TheFounderOfJainism|quote=Not in Copyright|authorlink=Champat Rai Jain}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Jainism topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Jainism and other religions|Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Hinduism and other religions]]\n", "name_user": "96.253.44.123", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_and_Hinduism"}
{"title_page": "Cheick Modibo Diarra", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Cheick Modibo Diarra\n|image       = Cheick Modibo Diarra 2010-09.jpg\n|office      = [[List of heads of government of Mali|Prime Minister of Mali]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n|president   = [[Dioncounda Traor\u00e9]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|term_start  = 17 April 2012\n|term_end    = 11 December 2012\n|predecessor = [[Ciss\u00e9 Mariam Ka\u00efdama Sidib\u00e9]]\n|successor   = [[Django Sissoko]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1952}}\n|birth_place = [[Nioro du Sahel]], [[French Sudan]]<br />{{small|(now [[Mali]])}}\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = Rally for the Development of Mali\n|alma_mater  = [[Pierre-and-Marie-Curie University|Pierre and Marie Curie University]]<br />[[Howard University]]\n}}\n'''Cheick Modibo Diarra''' (born 1952) is a [[Mali]]an [[astrophysicist]], businessman, and politician who was [[Prime Minister of Mali|acting Prime Minister of Mali]] from April 2012 to December 2012.\n\nOn 11 December 2012, Diarra presented his resignation on state television in a broadcast at 4 a.m. local time, hours after soldiers who led the [[2012 Malian coup d'\u00e9tat]] arrested him at his home in [[Bamako]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mali PM Cheik Modibo Diarra resigns after army arrest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20674573|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=11 December 2012|work=BBC News|date=2012-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career== He was the bigesst of them all \nDiarra was born in [[Nioro du Sahel]], Mali. He is the son-in-law of former president [[Moussa Traor\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Les partis politiques au Mali | url=http://www.afrique-express.com/afrique/mali/mali-partis-politiques.html | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206130828/http://www.afrique-express.com/afrique/mali/mali-partis-politiques.html | archivedate=2012-02-06 }}</ref>  After graduating high school in Mali, Cheick Modibo Diarra studied [[mathematics]], [[physics]], and analytic mechanics in [[Paris]] at the [[University of Paris|University of Pierre and Marie Curie]]. He then received a Masters in [[aerospace engineering]] and a [[PhD]] in [[mechanical engineering]], both from [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]  He was recruited by [[Caltech]]'s [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]], a NASA Federally Funded Research and Development Center ([[FFRDC]]) under a contractor with the California Institute of Technology, where he played a role in several [[NASA]] programs, including the [[Magellan probe]] to [[Venus]], the [[Ulysses probe]] to the [[Sun]], the [[Galileo spacecraft]] to [[Jupiter]], and the [[Mars Observer]] and [[Mars Pathfinder]].  He later became the director of [[Science outreach|education and public outreach]] for NASA's Mars Exploration program.<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA's Mars Exploration Education Project|url=http://mars.jpl.nasa.gov/MPF/education/cheick-diarra.html|publisher=NASA'S Jet Propulsion Laboratory|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref> Dr. Diarra also served as an executive for the Microsoft Corporation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Microsoft Press Release |url=http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/emea/presscentre/ExecutiveBiographies/CheickModiboDiarra.mspx |accessdate=24 November 2012 |newspaper=Microsoft Press Release |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622220052/http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/emea/presscentre/ExecutiveBiographies/CheickModiboDiarra.mspx |archivedate=22 June 2012 }}</ref> He also obtained [[Citizenship in the United States|American citizenship]].<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2012/04/19/un-cerveau-de-la-nasa-a-la-tete-du-gouvernement-malien_1687514_3212.html \"Un cerveau de la NASA \u00e0 la t\u00eate du gouvernement malien\"], ''Le Monde'', 19 April 2012 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he obtained permission from NASA to work part-time in order to devote himself to education development in [[Africa]], founding the Pathfinder Foundation.  He took a further sabbatical in 2002 to found a laboratory in [[Bamako]], Mali for the development of [[solar energy]]. In 2000 and 2001 he also served as a goodwill ambassador for [[UNESCO]].  In 2002 and 2003 he served as CEO of the [[African Virtual University]], based in [[Kenya]].\n\nCheick Modibo Diarra was the chairman of [[Microsoft]] [[Africa]] from 2006 until the end of 2011. Turning to Malian politics, he founded the Rally for the Development of Mali, a political party, in March 2011, and he intended to stand as a candidate in the [[2012 Malian presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/04/2012417215625215390.html \"Profile: Mali's Cheick Modibo Diarra\"], Al Jazeera, 17 April 2012.</ref>\n\n===Acting Prime Minister===\nCheick Modibo Diarra was appointed as interim [[Prime Minister of Mali]] on 17 April 2012 to help restore civilian rule after the [[2012 Malian coup d'\u00e9tat|March 2012 ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']].<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite web |title=Mali names Microsoft Africa chief as interim PM |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=17 April 2012 |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/maliNews/idAFL6E8FH99V20120417 |accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> His government, composed of 24 members, was appointed on 25 April 2012. Three of the most important posts&mdash;the ministries for defense, internal security, and territorial administration&mdash;were assigned to officers associated with the military junta that seized power in March and retained an important role even after formally returning power to civilians. Otherwise, the government was composed of [[technocrat]]s rather than political figures.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gkTSJ6YKCv3j2iK70-5piz0t25_Q?docId=CNG.95f554f363a479cc7e9380c60eefcd80.a1 \"Mali's interim PM forms government\"], Agence France-Presse, 25 April 2012.</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2012, soldiers reportedly sent by coup leader Captain [[Amadou Sanogo]] arrested Diarra as he prepared to leave the country for a medical check-up in France. Shortly after his arrest, Diarra appeared on state television and announced his resignation and that of his government.<ref name=resignation>{{cite news|title=Mali PM Cheik Modibo Diarra resigns after army arrest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20674573|accessdate=11 December 2012|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=11 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2013, ALN, an alliance of independent top tier African law firms, announced the appointment of Diarra as its Chairman. Diarra succeeded John Miles, the CEO of J Miles & Co.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.africalegalnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/ALN-Chairman-Announcement.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109151732/http://www.africalegalnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/ALN-Chairman-Announcement.pdf |archivedate=2014-01-09 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050406173316/http://www.pathfinder-foundation.org/index.htm Pathfinder Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ciss\u00e9 Mariam Ka\u00efdama Sidib\u00e9]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Mali|Prime Minister of Mali]]<br />{{small|Acting}}|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Django Sissoko]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MaliPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diarra, Cheick Modibo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Malian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Malian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Malian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Malian scientists]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Mali]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kayes Region]]\n[[Category:UNESCO Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Cheick Modibo Diarra\n|image       = Cheick Modibo Diarra 2010-09.jpg\n|office      = [[List of heads of government of Mali|Prime Minister of Mali]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n|president   = [[Dioncounda Traor\u00e9]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|term_start  = 17 April 2012\n|term_end    = 11 December 2012\n|predecessor = [[Ciss\u00e9 Mariam Ka\u00efdama Sidib\u00e9]]\n|successor   = [[Django Sissoko]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1952}}\n|birth_place = [[Nioro du Sahel]], [[French Sudan]]<br />{{small|(now [[Mali]])}}\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = Rally for the Development of Mali\n|alma_mater  = [[Pierre-and-Marie-Curie University|Pierre and Marie Curie University]]<br />[[Howard University]]\n}}\n'''Cheick Modibo Diarra''' (born 1952) is a [[Mali]]an [[astrophysicist]], businessman, and politician who was [[Prime Minister of Mali|acting Prime Minister of Mali]] from April 2012 to December 2012.\n\nOn 11 December 2012, Diarra presented his resignation on state television in a broadcast at 4 a.m. local time, hours after soldiers who led the [[2012 Malian coup d'\u00e9tat]] arrested him at his home in [[Bamako]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mali PM Cheik Modibo Diarra resigns after army arrest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20674573|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=11 December 2012|work=BBC News|date=2012-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nDiarra was born in [[Nioro du Sahel]], Mali. He is the son-in-law of former president [[Moussa Traor\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Les partis politiques au Mali | url=http://www.afrique-express.com/afrique/mali/mali-partis-politiques.html | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206130828/http://www.afrique-express.com/afrique/mali/mali-partis-politiques.html | archivedate=2012-02-06 }}</ref>  After graduating high school in Mali, Cheick Modibo Diarra studied [[mathematics]], [[physics]], and analytic mechanics in [[Paris]] at the [[University of Paris|University of Pierre and Marie Curie]]. He then received a Masters in [[aerospace engineering]] and a [[PhD]] in [[mechanical engineering]], both from [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]  He was recruited by [[Caltech]]'s [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]], a NASA Federally Funded Research and Development Center ([[FFRDC]]) under a contractor with the California Institute of Technology, where he played a role in several [[NASA]] programs, including the [[Magellan probe]] to [[Venus]], the [[Ulysses probe]] to the [[Sun]], the [[Galileo spacecraft]] to [[Jupiter]], and the [[Mars Observer]] and [[Mars Pathfinder]].  He later became the director of [[Science outreach|education and public outreach]] for NASA's Mars Exploration program.<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA's Mars Exploration Education Project|url=http://mars.jpl.nasa.gov/MPF/education/cheick-diarra.html|publisher=NASA'S Jet Propulsion Laboratory|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref> Dr. Diarra also served as an executive for the Microsoft Corporation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Microsoft Press Release |url=http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/emea/presscentre/ExecutiveBiographies/CheickModiboDiarra.mspx |accessdate=24 November 2012 |newspaper=Microsoft Press Release |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622220052/http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/emea/presscentre/ExecutiveBiographies/CheickModiboDiarra.mspx |archivedate=22 June 2012 }}</ref> He also obtained [[Citizenship in the United States|American citizenship]].<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2012/04/19/un-cerveau-de-la-nasa-a-la-tete-du-gouvernement-malien_1687514_3212.html \"Un cerveau de la NASA \u00e0 la t\u00eate du gouvernement malien\"], ''Le Monde'', 19 April 2012 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he obtained permission from NASA to work part-time in order to devote himself to education development in [[Africa]], founding the Pathfinder Foundation.  He took a further sabbatical in 2002 to found a laboratory in [[Bamako]], Mali for the development of [[solar energy]]. In 2000 and 2001 he also served as a goodwill ambassador for [[UNESCO]].  In 2002 and 2003 he served as CEO of the [[African Virtual University]], based in [[Kenya]].\n\nCheick Modibo Diarra was the chairman of [[Microsoft]] [[Africa]] from 2006 until the end of 2011. Turning to Malian politics, he founded the Rally for the Development of Mali, a political party, in March 2011, and he intended to stand as a candidate in the [[2012 Malian presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/04/2012417215625215390.html \"Profile: Mali's Cheick Modibo Diarra\"], Al Jazeera, 17 April 2012.</ref>\n\n===Acting Prime Minister===\nCheick Modibo Diarra was appointed as interim [[Prime Minister of Mali]] on 17 April 2012 to help restore civilian rule after the [[2012 Malian coup d'\u00e9tat|March 2012 ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']].<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite web |title=Mali names Microsoft Africa chief as interim PM |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=17 April 2012 |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/maliNews/idAFL6E8FH99V20120417 |accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> His government, composed of 24 members, was appointed on 25 April 2012. Three of the most important posts&mdash;the ministries for defense, internal security, and territorial administration&mdash;were assigned to officers associated with the military junta that seized power in March and retained an important role even after formally returning power to civilians. Otherwise, the government was composed of [[technocrat]]s rather than political figures.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gkTSJ6YKCv3j2iK70-5piz0t25_Q?docId=CNG.95f554f363a479cc7e9380c60eefcd80.a1 \"Mali's interim PM forms government\"], Agence France-Presse, 25 April 2012.</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2012, soldiers reportedly sent by coup leader Captain [[Amadou Sanogo]] arrested Diarra as he prepared to leave the country for a medical check-up in France. Shortly after his arrest, Diarra appeared on state television and announced his resignation and that of his government.<ref name=resignation>{{cite news|title=Mali PM Cheik Modibo Diarra resigns after army arrest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20674573|accessdate=11 December 2012|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=11 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2013, ALN, an alliance of independent top tier African law firms, announced the appointment of Diarra as its Chairman. Diarra succeeded John Miles, the CEO of J Miles & Co.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.africalegalnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/ALN-Chairman-Announcement.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109151732/http://www.africalegalnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/ALN-Chairman-Announcement.pdf |archivedate=2014-01-09 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050406173316/http://www.pathfinder-foundation.org/index.htm Pathfinder Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ciss\u00e9 Mariam Ka\u00efdama Sidib\u00e9]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Mali|Prime Minister of Mali]]<br />{{small|Acting}}|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Django Sissoko]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MaliPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diarra, Cheick Modibo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Malian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Malian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Malian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Malian scientists]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Mali]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kayes Region]]\n[[Category:UNESCO Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n", "name_user": "71.208.128.19", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLife and career)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheick_Modibo_Diarra"}
{"title_page": "2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship", "text_new": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship\n| year = 2020\n| other_titles = <!--Tournament name in native language of hosts-->\n| image =\n| size = 250px\n| country = Mexico\n| city =\n| dates = Postponed<br />(originally 18 April \u2013 3 May 2020)\n| num_teams = 20\n| confederations = 1\n| venues = TBC\n| cities = 1\n| champion_other = <!--{{fbwu|17|}}-->\n| count =\n| second_other = <!--{{fbwu|17|}}-->\n| third_other = <!--{{fbwu|17|}}-->\n| fourth_other = <!--{{fbwu|17|}}-->\n| matches =\n| goals =\n| attendance =\n| top_scorer =\n| player =\n| goalkeeper =\n| fair_play =\n| prevseason = [[2018 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship|2018]]\n| nextseason = [[2022 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship|2022]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship''' will be the 7th edition of the [[CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship]], the biennial international youth [[association football|football]] championship organised by [[CONCACAF]] for the women's under-17 national teams of the North, Central American and Caribbean region. The tournament was originally scheduled to be held in [[Mexico]] between 18 April and 3 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/under-17s-women/article/mexico-named-host-for-2020-concacaf-women-s-under-17-championship|title=Mexico Named Host for 2020 Concacaf Women's Under-17 Championship|publisher=CONCACAF.com|date=31 January 2020}}</ref> However, on 19 March 2020, CONCACAF announced the decision to postpone the tournament due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], with the new dates of the tournament to be confirmed later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/article/concacaf-statement-on-additional-tournament-suspensions|title=Concacaf Statement on Additional Tournament Suspensions|publisher=CONCACAF|date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe final tournament is expanded from eight to 20 teams, using the same format as the [[2019 CONCACAF U-17 Championship]]. The top three teams of the tournament will qualify for the [[2020 FIFA U-17 Women's World Cup]] in [[India]] as the CONCACAF representatives.\n\n[[United States women's national under-17 soccer team|United States]] are the defending champions.\n\n==Qualified teams==\n{{Details|2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage}}\n\nThe qualifying format has changed since the 2018 edition, and the teams are no longer divided into regional zones.\n\nThe 41 [[CONCACAF]] teams were ranked based on the CONCACAF Women's Under-17 Ranking as of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/rankings/womens-under-17|title=Concacaf Women's Under-17 Ranking|publisher=CONCACAF.com}}</ref> A total of 32 teams entered the tournament. The highest-ranked 16 entrants were exempt from qualifying and advanced directly to the group stage of the final tournament, while the lowest-ranked 16 entrants had to participate in the qualifying stage, where the four group winners advanced to the round of 16 of the knockout stage of the final tournament.<ref name=\"draw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/under-17s-women/article/concacaf-announces-details-for-the-2020-concacaf-women-s-under-17-championship|title=Concacaf Announces Details for the 2020 Concacaf Women's Under-17 Championship|publisher=CONCACAF.com|date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Round\n!width=200px| Team\n!width=180px| Qualification\n!width=120px data-sort-type=\"number\"| Appearance\n!width=320px| Previous best performance\n!width=100px| Previous [[FIFA U-17 Women's World Cup]] appearances\n|-\n|align=center rowspan=16| Group stage\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|MEX}} <small>(hosts)</small>\n|align=center| {{sort|01|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|1st ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 5\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|CAN}}\n|align=center| {{sort|02|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|2nd ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 6\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|USA}} <small>([[2018 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship|title holders]])</small>\n|align=center| {{sort|03|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|3rd ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 4\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|HAI}}\n|align=center| {{sort|04|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|4th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|CRC}}\n|align=center| {{sort|05|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|5th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 2\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|JAM}}\n|align=center| {{sort|06|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|6th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|TRI}}\n|align=center| {{sort|07|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|7th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 1\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|GUA}}\n|align=center| {{sort|08|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|8th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|PUR}}\n|align=center| {{sort|09|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|9th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|BER}}\n|align=center| {{sort|10|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|10th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|SLV}}\n|align=center| {{sort|11|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|11th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|PAN}}\n|align=center| {{sort|12|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|12th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|DOM}}\n|align=center| {{sort|13|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|13th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|CUB}}\n|align=center| {{sort|14|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|14th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|GRN}}\n|align=center| {{sort|15|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|15th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|NCA}}\n|align=center| {{sort|16|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Teams|16th ranked]] entrant}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=center rowspan=4| Knockout stage\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|HON}}\n|align=center| {{sort|A|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Group A|Qualifying Group A]] winner}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|CAY}}\n|align=center| {{sort|B|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Group B|Qualifying Group B]] winner}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|BLZ}}\n|align=center| {{sort|C|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Group C|Qualifying Group C]] winner}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{fbwu|17|GUY}}\n|align=center| {{sort|D|[[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage#Group D|Qualifying Group D]] winner}}\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center| 0\n|}\n\n==Venues==\n*[[Mexican Football Federation]] Headquarters, [[Toluca]]\n\n==Draw==\nThe draw for the group stage took place on 9 May 2019, 11:00 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] ([[UTC\u221204:00|UTC\u22124]]), at the CONCACAF Headquarters in [[Miami]]. The 16 teams which entered the group stage were drawn into four groups of four teams.<ref name=\"draw\"/> Based on the CONCACAF Women's Under-17 Ranking, the 16 teams were distributed into four pots, with teams in Pot 1 assigned to each group prior to the draw, as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/under-17s-women/video/official-draw-2020-concacaf-women-s-under-17-championship|title=Official draw \u2013 2020 CONCACAF Women's Under-17 Championship|publisher=CONCACAF.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Pot 1\n!Pot 2\n!Pot 3\n!Pot 4\n|-\n|valign=top|{{plainlist|\n*{{fbwu|17|MEX}} (E1)\n*{{fbwu|17|CAN}} (F1)\n*{{fbwu|17|USA}} (G1)\n*{{fbwu|17|HAI}} (H1)\n}}\n|valign=top|{{plainlist|\n*{{fbwu|17|CRC}}\n*{{fbwu|17|JAM}}\n*{{fbwu|17|TRI}}\n*{{fbwu|17|GUA}}\n}}\n|valign=top|{{plainlist|\n*{{fbwu|17|PUR}}\n*{{fbwu|17|BER}}\n*{{fbwu|17|SLV}}\n*{{fbwu|17|PAN}}\n}}\n|valign=top|{{plainlist|\n*{{fbwu|17|DOM}}\n*{{fbwu|17|CUB}}\n*{{fbwu|17|GRN}}\n*{{fbwu|17|NCA}}\n}}\n|}\n\n==Squads==\n{{Details|2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship squads}}\n\nPlayers born on or after 1 January 2003 are eligible to compete. Each team must register a squad of 20 players, two of whom must be goalkeepers.<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=https://res.cloudinary.com/concacaf-production/image/upload/v1581353741/concacaf-prod/assets/Concacaf_Women_s_Under-17_Championship_-_Regulations_ENG.pdf|title=2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship Regulations|publisher=CONCACAF}}</ref>\n\n==Group stage==\nThe top three teams in each group will advance to the round of 16, where they are joined by the four teams advancing from the [[2020 CONCACAF Women's U-17 Championship qualifying stage|qualifying stage]].\n{{anchor|Tiebreakers}}\n;Tiebreakers\nThe ranking of teams in each group is determined as follows (Regulations Article 12.8):<ref name=\"regulations\"/>\n#[[Points (association football)|Points]] obtained in all group matches (three points for a win, one for a draw, zero for a loss);\n#[[Goal difference]] in all group matches;\n#Number of goals scored in all group matches;\n#Points obtained in the matches played between the teams in question;\n#Goal difference in the matches played between the teams in question;\n#Number of goals scored in the matches played between the teams in question;\n#Fair play points in all group matches (only one deduction could be applied to a player in a single match):\n#*Yellow card: \u22121 points;\n#*Indirect red card (second yellow card): \u22123 points;\n#*Direct red card: \u22124 points;\n#*Yellow card and direct red card: \u22125 points;\n#Drawing of lots.\n\nAll times are local, [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gallery.mailchimp.com/78d3589fb61466b549ff752e5/files/32736f24-e628-4894-a6cb-a3c6f3f05e50/CWU17C_2020_Schedule_Announcement.pdf|title=2020 Match Schedule|publisher=CONCACAF}}</ref>\n\n===Group E===\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n\n|source=[https://www.concacaf.com/en/under-17s-women/schedule-results#tab_team=standings CONCACAF]\n|name_MEX={{fbwu|17|MEX}}\n|name_TRI={{fbwu|17|TRI}}\n|name_BER={{fbwu|17|BER}}\n|name_DOM={{fbwu|17|DOM}}\n\n<!--UPDATE standings below (including date)-->\n|update=future |start_date=TBD\n|win_MEX=0 |draw_MEX=0 |loss_MEX=0 |gf_MEX=0 |ga_MEX=0 |status_MEX=H\n|win_TRI=0 |draw_TRI=0 |loss_TRI=0 |gf_TRI=0 |ga_TRI=0 |status_TRI=\n|win_BER=0 |draw_BER=0 |loss_BER=0 |gf_BER=0 |ga_BER=0 |status_BER=\n|win_DOM=0 |draw_DOM=0 |loss_DOM=0 |gf_DOM=0 |ga_DOM=0 |status_DOM=\n\n<!--UPDATE positions below (check tiebreakers)-->\n|team1=MEX |team2=TRI |team3=BER |team4=DOM\n|class_rules=[[#Tiebreakers|Group stage tiebreakers]]\n\n|res_col_header=Q\n|result1=KO |result2=KO |result3=KO\n|col_KO=green1 |text_KO=[[#Knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n}}\n\n{{Football box\n|date       = <!--{{Start date|2020|